East Palo Alto ADU Local Ordinance Policy Analysis

City Systems

4/10/2020

\(~\)

1 Introduction

The City of EPA is developing its local ADU ordinance and needs to decide how much local discretion to apply on top of the new state ADU laws. There is a range of ADU eligibility from the least restrictive, where the state law is adopted without any local discrtion, to themost restrictive" where the most local discretion is applied that is allowed under state law. This document presents ADU eligibility in EPA under these different scenarios to help inform staff recommendations, community perspective, Planning Commission recommendations, and the City Councils final decision.

The key local discretionary choices being considered are:

  • Street setback (none, to house, or 12ft)
  • Min rear yard open space (none or 50% existing)
  • Max ADU size (1200 sqft or 1000 sqft)
  • Property setback (4ft or 6ft)
  • Max site coverage (none or 50%)
  • Max floor area ratio (none or 55%)

Note that none of the above local discretionary add-ons can prevent a 800 SF ADU. They can only create a maximum size restriction on ADUs that would have been in the 800-1200 sqft range.

  • Maximum number of rooms (unlimited or 3) is also being considered by EPA, but since this does not affect parcel viability, its not dealt with in this analysis.

Given the above choices, we have prepared a sequence of scenarios starting from least restrictive (the state law with no local discretion) then increasing in restrictiveness on ADUs through different likely combinations of the above choices. The primary measure of restrictiveness is the number of ADUs that can be built in the 800+ (greater than 800) sqft range. Four analysis results are shown in this summary table (with much more detail in the specific sections for each scenario): the # of parcels that can build only up to 800 sqft ADUs, attached and detached, and the # of parcels that can build 800+ sqft ADUs, attached and detached (note there is overlap between attached/detached categories). The total number of ADU-eligible parcels is always 4157 as a result of state law.

Of residentially zoned parcels, below is the breakdown of property use code according to the County Assessor, which should represent as of early 2019 the existing use. The table also notes which PUCs we considered to be ADU eligible for our analysis, and completed the buildable area analysis for. Note the following key caveats:

  • PUC 91 and 92 are likely existing permitted ADU parcels. There are likely many other unpermitted ADUs under PUC 1.
  • If a residentially zoned lot is currently vacant (PUC: 0), buildable area analysis wasnt performed. But if the property owner were to build a residential building, then its likely they would also subsequently be able to build an ADU. So our ADU numbers will be underestimates because they dont include currently vacant residential lots.
  • Larger multifamily buildings (5+ units) are not included in the buildable area analysis, although they are technically ADU eligible. Such buildings are typically very differently designed than low-density housing, and have their own special state ADU regulations. We would assume that most of the ADU opportunities for such buildings are internal ADU conversions.

The table includes some additional statistics. % owner occupied is the number for which there is a listed homeowner tax exemption OR the owners mailing address matches the property address.

2.3 Residential Property Use Code Summary

residential_puc_summary <-
  data %>%
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>% 
  filter(
    Zoning %in% 
      c(
        "R-HD (Multi-Family High Density Residential)",
        "R-LD (Single-Family Residential)",
        "R-MD-1 (Multi-Family Medium Density Residential)",
        "R-MD-2 (Multi-Family Medium Density Residential)",
        "R-UHD (Multi-Family Urban High Density Residential)",
        "Urban Residential"
      )
  ) %>% 
  group_by(PUC) %>% 
  summarize(
    Count = n(),
    `Median Lot Size` = median(parcel_area, na.rm=T) %>% round(),
    `Median Gross Bldg Sqft` = median(`GROSS BUILDING SQFT`, na.rm=T) %>% round(),
    `In Flood Zone` = sum(!is.na(FLD_ZONE)),
    `# of Units` = sum(UNITS,na.rm=T),
    `% Owner Occupied` = sum(`EXEMPTION CODE`=="HO" | ADDRESS != substr(`OWNER MAILING ADDRESS`,1,nchar(ADDRESS)),na.rm=T)/n()*100,
    `% Owner Occupied` = `% Owner Occupied` %>% round()
  ) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(PUC)) %>% 
  filter(PUC <= 5 | PUC >= 89) %>% 
  left_join(read_csv("smc_puc.csv"), by="PUC") %>% 
  dplyr::select(PUC, `PUC Description`, Categorization = type, everything()) %>% 
  mutate(
    Categorization = 
      case_when(
        Categorization == "other" ~ "Other",
        Categorization == "adu eligible" ~ "ADU Eligible",
        TRUE ~ "Other Residential"
      )
  )

3 Scenario A (Least Restrictive): State regs without local discretion

The following map shows all buildable area for attached and detached ADUs in East Palo Alto in the least restrictive scenario, which essentially allows attached and detached ADUs in the 800-1000 sqft range. Note we have assumed the states ministerial 4ft rear/side setback is applied to the house and front as well; these are variables that can be changed with local discretion.

The instructions below will apply to all other maps too:

  • Hover over parcels to see addresses. Existing buildings and buildable area are only mapped for residential parcels.
  • The green region is detached ADU buildable area. Its 4ft from side/rear, 6ft from existing buildings, no closer to the street than the existing building, and can fit at least an 8ft x 20ft structure. Click to see the maximum detached ADU that can be built on the green area of the parcel. This is capped at 1,200 sqft per state regulations, even if the green space is much larger. Hover over to see the sqft of the buildable area.
  • The blue shape is an example detached ADU. For now, this just shows three possible sizes: 160 sqft, 448 sqft (HEARTs studio), or 640 sqft (HEARTs 1BR), generally set as far as possible away from existing structures (sometimes this is shown in the front yard, which may be realistic; you can imagine placing another blue rectangle anywhere there is green). Hover over to see the sqft of the example ADU.
  • The yellow region (including green) is attached ADU buildable area. It doesnt have the 6ft setback from existing buildings. Click to see the maximum attached ADU that can be built on the parcel. This is capped at 50% of existing gross building sqft or 1,200 sqft. Hover over to see the sqft of the buildable area.
  • This Drive folder has the raw data (including owner names and many Assessor building characteristics) in CSV form, as well as shapefile versions based on parcel geometry, building geometry, and attached/detached buildable area geometries.
  • More information about the methodology and data sources will be prepared in an Appendix soon.

load("epa_sfha.Rdata")

epa_boundary <-
  places("CA", cb=FALSE) %>% 
  filter(NAME == "East Palo Alto") %>%

long <- map_center[1]
lat <- map_center[2]

data_4s4h <-
  data %>% 
  mutate(
    furthest_adu = 
      ifelse(
        !is.na(st_dimension(detached_heart16x40_4s4h_furthest_adu)),
        detached_heart16x40_4s4h_furthest_adu,
        ifelse(
          !is.na(st_dimension(detached_heart16x28_4s4h_furthest_adu)),
          detached_heart16x28_4s4h_furthest_adu,
          detached_4s4h_furthest_adu
        )
      ) %>% st_sfc() %>% st_set_crs(projection),
    furthest_adu_area = st_area(furthest_adu) %>% as.numeric() %>% round(),
    max_attached_4s_buildable_area =
      ifelse(
        is.na(max_attached_4s_buildable_area),
        NA,
        pmin(
          ifelse(
            is.na(`GROSS BUILDING SQFT`),
            building_geometry %>% st_area(.)/2,
            `GROSS BUILDING SQFT`/2
          ),
          1200,
          max_attached_4s_buildable_area
        )
      ),
    max_attached_4s_buildable_area =
      floor(max_attached_4s_buildable_area/10)*10,
    max_detached_4s4h_buildable_area =
      pmin(1200,max_detached_4s4h_buildable_area)
  )

4 Scenario B: 12ft from street

Scenario B removes 12ft of setback from all street edges, including front yard and street sides on corner lots, from ADU development.

Note that if the parcel could build an 800 sqft ADU in the front yard in the least restrictive scenario, then the Casita Coalitions interpretation of the state law through HCD correspondence is that a local discretionary rule cannot prevent a homeowner from choosing to build a detached or attached ADU in the front yard. Our analysis currently doesnt specifically identify whether an 800 sqft ADU can be built in a front yard; besides, we suspect this will not ultimately be desired by the City or its residents. But this analysis can be added in the future.

4.1 Scenario B: Detailed Map

data_4s4h12f <-

data_4s6hXf <-
  data %>% 
  mutate(
    furthest_adu = 
      ifelse(
        !is.na(st_dimension(detached_heart16x40_4s6hXf_furthest_adu)),
        detached_heart16x40_4s6hXf_furthest_adu,
        ifelse(
          !is.na(st_dimension(detached_heart16x28_4s6hXf_furthest_adu)),
          detached_heart16x28_4s6hXf_furthest_adu,
          detached_4s6hXf_furthest_adu
        )
      ) %>% st_sfc() %>% st_set_crs(projection),
    furthest_adu_area = st_area(furthest_adu) %>% as.numeric() %>% round(),
    max_attached_4sXf_buildable_area =
      ifelse(
        is.na(max_attached_4sXf_buildable_area),
        NA,
        pmin(
          ifelse(
            is.na(`GROSS BUILDING SQFT`),
            building_geometry %>% st_area(.)/2,
            `GROSS BUILDING SQFT`/2
          ),
          1200,
          max_attached_4sXf_buildable_area
        )
      ),
    max_attached_4sXf_buildable_area =
      floor(max_attached_4sXf_buildable_area/10)*10,
    max_detached_4s6hXf_buildable_area =
      pmin(1200,max_detached_4s6hXf_buildable_area)
  )

8 Scenario F: No front yard ADUs + Maintain EPA property setback + Limit max size + Maintain rear space

Scenario F adds a minimum rear space of 50%. To model this, we took the original backyard buildable area for each parcel (specifically scenario C detached ADU buildable area, expanded 4ft) and assume that to be rear space. For each parcel, we add a limitation that the attached or detached ADU can be no larger than 50% of this buildable area.

The detailed map will be the same as Scenario D (except for some example ADUs which may be too big in this scenario), but we will now show the summary table, summary map, and histograms.

9 Scenario G: No front yard ADUs + Maintain EPA property setback + Limit max size + Maintain rear space + Limit SC/FAR

Scenario G adds a maximum site coverage of 50% and floor area ratio 55%. We will model both effects at the same time. Site coverage is straightforward because we have easy access to site area for each parcel. Floor area ratio is based on the best information we have about the gross building square footage which comes from the San Mateo County Tax Assessors building characteristics data (but we have less confidence about this data).

The detailed map will be the same as Scenario D (except for some example ADUs which may be too big in this scenario), but we will now show the summary table, summary map, and histograms.
